Feature: a published bc-launcher image carries its bc-launcher version and baked shop-templates version as inspectable OCI-label + ENV provenance, so docker image inspect surfaces the right versions rather than the misleading upstream base label

  Pins lead-5xnd (step 1 of the version-management roadmap). Today the published
  images carry NO shopsystem version provenance: bc-base:latest's only "version"
  label is the upstream devcontainer base's "version=3.1.2" — misleading, since
  it is NOT the shopsystem/bc-launcher version, and nothing identifies the
  bc-launcher release or the baked shop-templates version. Tags cannot close the
  gap: ":latest" and ":vX.Y.Z" are the same digest and the run-tag is not
  recoverable from a pulled image or a running container. The values already
  exist at build time (the bc-launcher Dockerfile takes shop-templates as a
  build-arg pin and self-pins the launcher version at the tag); they are simply
  not emitted as provenance.

  This scenario pins the OBSERVABLE provenance contract — what "docker image
  inspect" surfaces — NOT the Dockerfile mechanism that produces it (the BC owns
  LABEL/ENV authoring and the publish-workflow build-arg wiring). The named label
  and env keys ARE the contract surface, because downstream consumers read them
  by name: bootstrap baked-version verify (lead-b2iz) becomes a docker-inspect /
  printenv check instead of a pip-show, and bin/doctor (lead-q3r1) can report the
  version from these keys. The contract spans BOTH published images — bc-base and
  bc-lead — so the Examples table enumerates both. A published image that omits
  any of these labels/env, or that surfaces "3.1.2" as the version, fails this
  scenario. (Targets shopsystem-bc-launcher: the bc-base/bc-lead Dockerfiles and
  the publish workflow.)

  @scenario_hash:7c0c949fccdf9df2
  Scenario Outline: a published bc-launcher image surfaces its bc-launcher release version and baked shop-templates version via OCI labels and ENV, overriding the misleading upstream base version label
    Given the bc-launcher publish workflow built and published the "<image>" image at bc-launcher release version "v0.3.38" baking shop-templates version "v0.47.0"
    When the published "<image>:latest" image is examined with "docker image inspect"
    Then the image's "org.opencontainers.image.version" OCI label equals the bc-launcher release version "v0.3.38"
    And the image's "org.opencontainers.image.revision" OCI label is a non-empty git commit sha identifying the source revision the image was built from
    And the image's "shopsystem.shop-templates.version" OCI label equals the baked shop-templates version "v0.47.0"
    And the image's configured environment includes "SHOPSYSTEM_BC_LAUNCHER_VERSION" equal to the bc-launcher release version "v0.3.38"
    And the image's configured environment includes "SHOP_TEMPLATES_VERSION" equal to the baked shop-templates version "v0.47.0"
    And the bc-launcher version surfaced by inspect is "v0.3.38" rather than the upstream devcontainer base label value "3.1.2"

    Examples:
      | image                               |
      | ghcr.io/dstengle/shopsystem-bc-base |
      | ghcr.io/dstengle/shopsystem-bc-lead |
